<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Christabel</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Initiate<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Mar 2001<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>This is like the 5th post I've read on the topic. And I've gotta say, good for greece. I think a lot of talent and potential is thrown away through obsessive gaming. Even going back to the day of MUDs, there were no shortage of people flunking out of school, ruining their marriages, getting fired from their jobs, and blowing up like baloons as they phased out real life in exchange for virtual life. And as these online games become more refined, they'll only become more immersive.<br />
<br />
You can talk about various American ideals, like freedom of choice. But there are certain freedoms that cause more harm than good (salt, sugar, fat, tobacco, alcohol, etc). Nothing like this would ever happen in the US. And that's fine with me. But if the greeks can pull it off, more power to them.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
