	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />It's hypocritical to laud this move and still keep your EQ account.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>I haven't owned an EQ account in nearly 6 months. And my point is <u>not</u> that all the things I listed are bad for every single individual. It's that each one of them, in the big picture, is detrimental.<br />
<br />
For example... some people can smoke occasionally and get away with it. But when you consider that 90% of lung cancer cases are caused exclusively by smoking, it puts the big picture of tobacco in perspective. For your casual drinkers you have your drunk drivers and alcoholics. And in contrast to your weekend diners you have morbidly obese walking time bombs coming down with diseases that would be virtually non-existant if it wasn't for their undisciplined habits.<br />
<br />
Online gaming is a thing that's entertaining at it's very best (and nothing more)... but very destructive at its worst. So like I say, if greece can pull this off, kudos to them. Some people need to be protected from their own stupidity... particularly in countries with socialized health care and entitlement programs. One person's problems are paid for out of the next person's wallet.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
