	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" /><i>Originally posted by Megumi </i><br />
<b>Does anyone else see something strange about a Greek law being at the mercy of review by a European court?  It's one thing for the Greek government to come up with something as stupid and misguided as this law.  But, where's their sovereignty?  Is Europe really this far down the path to command-and-control?  I suppose that begging the UN for permission to do anything is next. </b><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Not quite but anyone who is convicted under a law such as this has this has the right to appeal to the European court of human rights. Every country that signed up to EEC (European Economic Community) agreed to this. <br />
<br />
I think it's similar to what happens with the states in North America. If one state decides to make a law and you are convicted because you broke this law. Is their not a court that you can appeal to, to see if the law is fair and just?<br />
<br />
If the court decideds that the law is fair then it stays, but if the court decides that it's not then the government have to change it. It's not uncommon for new laws to get "tested" in this way</p>
	
	
	
