	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" /><i>Originally posted by Christabel </i><br />
<b><br />
<br />
Again... you can't lump useful and productive things in with mere entertainment (even if those things have a potential for harm or abuse). Banning computers and internet access, would be similar to banning cars. Banning frivolous activities like online gaming is another story all together.<br />
<br />
Definition of good: those things which produce more benefit than detriment<br />
<br />
Definition of bad: Oposite of good.<img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /><br />
<br />
So if you have a thing which, at it's best, is not capable of providing anything more than entertainment, but at its worst can be used by people to ruin their lives... I support the right of the greek government to not pick up the tab for it.<br />
<br />
 <img src="images/smilies/wink.gif" border="0" alt="" title="wink" smilieid="5" /> </b><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Entertainment is good and desireable.  There's "quality of life"... we're not ants slaving away for the good of the hive here, drones who need no entertainment or pleasures.  Life, libert, and pursuit of happiness.<br />
<br />
Cars at best improve quality of life.  No, they are not 100% necessary.  At worst, they pollute the environment and can ruin someone's life if they have an accident which cripples or kills someone.  Ban cars.<br />
<br />
Sorry Christabel, but your logic has more holes in it than swiss cheese.  Or is it feta? <img src="images/smilies/eek.gif" border="0" alt="" title="eek!" smilieid="10" /><br />
<br />
Edit: I support the right of the greek government to ban electronic games.  I also support the right of human beings everywhere to decry it as totalitarian, invasive, and doing nothing to serve the public good.</p>
	
	
	
