<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>BlargX</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Guest<br />
		
	
	<br />
	
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Megumi, your political shtick is pretty out of line here, both calling people "left wingers" and doing so as if it were an insult.  Why don't you tell us which religion you dislike the most, too? (yawn)<br />
<br />
Anyway, if we're going to look at the human(not left wing or right wing) impulse to control other people and tell them what to do, we'll find it pretty universal on any side of any political divide. It's an expression of power.  And life is all about power.  <br />
<br />
Puts me in mind of an article I read in Harpers or The Atlantic this month, where someone is quoted as saying something like, "Given absolute power over another person, the human mind turns to torture."  Torturing, for people who do it for pleasure rather than just as part of their daily job, is just an extension of control, after all, and an ultimate expression of power.  <br />
<br />
Power is a primal human need.  People will do the craziest things to no other purpose than to express their power -- harass their employees, rape, engage in pointless wars, redecorate a new mate's home, decorate and mutilate their own bodies or those of their enemies, abuse their pets and children, climb mountains, commit all sorts of wrongs or just do crazy things.<br />
<br />
It's unfortunate when people want to express power just to express power.  Making laws that control behavior that's really nobody's business is always a popular one -- religious laws or civil laws.  Most states in America have had laws about what kind of sex people can have with each other, and many still have them on the books.  There was the missionary way and the WRONG way, I guess.  Oral sex was prohibited all over the place, sometimes still is.  <br />
<br />
Then there are all the other victimless crimes, and different ways to describe victimhood, depending on what your perspective is.<br />
<br />
All of which are nobody's business.  The law isn't supposed to be there to tell you how to live; it's supposed to be there to organize the societal institutions you need to keep people living together without harming each other, and to defend the populace from aggression by other peoples and nations.<br />
<br />
Frankly, I could give a rat's ass about any legislator or president or religious figurehead's ideas about anything.  I just need them to make sure there are firemen and cops and sewer systems and electricity and water around when I need them, that kind of thing.<br />
<br />
The last thing you want is people "only" restricting video games.  The idea that it's anybody's business to tell you how to live your life or force you to act or not act accordingly is a horrible one, and always subject to the arbitrary whims of the mob of the minute or the king of the month.  <br />
<br />
When I want some nosy punk of a goober telling me how to live, I'll open up his stinking hole and feed him a fish.  Otherwise, he can mind his own goddamn business and just fix the potholes outside my house, please.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
